{"parse":{"title":"Ludus (ancient Rome)","pageid":11801157,"revid":795593958,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg/220px-Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"330\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg/330px-Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg/440px-Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2304\" data-file-height=\"3456\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Roman_statue_of_girl_playing_astragaloi_14_aC.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Roman girl at play (<i>ludus</i>) with <a href=\"/wiki/Knucklebones\" title=\"Knucklebones\">knucklebones</a></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg/220px-Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"183\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg/330px-Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg/440px-Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"450\" data-file-height=\"375\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Xii_scripta_ephesus.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Gaming table for <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ludus_duodecim_scriptorum\" title=\"Ludus duodecim scriptorum\">ludus duodecim scriptorum</a></i></div></div></div>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Culture_of_ancient_Rome\" title=\"Culture of ancient Rome\">ancient Roman culture</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Latin\" title=\"Latin\">Latin</a> word <i><b>ludus</b></i> (plural <i>ludi</i>) has several meanings within the <a href=\"/wiki/Semantic_field\" title=\"Semantic field\">semantic field</a> of \"play, game, sport, training\" (see also <a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/ludic\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikt:ludic\">ludic</a>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>An <a href=\"/wiki/Elementary_school\" title=\"Elementary school\">elementary</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Primary_school\" title=\"Primary school\">primary school</a> or the school of the \u201clitterator\" attended by boys and girls up to the age of 11 was a <i>ludus</i>. <i>Ludi</i> were to be found throughout the city, and were run by a <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ludi_magister\" title=\"Ludi magister\">ludi magister</a></i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Schoolmaster\" title=\"Schoolmaster\">schoolmaster</a>) who was often an educated <a href=\"/wiki/Slavery_in_ancient_Rome\" title=\"Slavery in ancient Rome\">slave</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Freedman\" title=\"Freedman\">freedman</a>. School started around six o'clock each morning and finished just after midday. Students were taught math, reading, writing, poetry, geometry and sometimes rhetoric.\n</p><p>The word <i>ludus</i> also referred to a training school for gladiators; see <a href=\"/wiki/Gladiator#Schools_and_training\" title=\"Gladiator\">Gladiator: Schools and training</a>. Examples include the <a href=\"/wiki/Ludus_Magnus\" title=\"Ludus Magnus\">Ludus Magnus</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Ludus_Dacicus\" title=\"Ludus Dacicus\">Ludus Dacicus</a>.\n</p><p><i>Ludus</i> was also the word for a board game, examples of which include <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ludus_latrunculorum\" title=\"Ludus latrunculorum\">ludus latrunculorum</a></i> and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ludus_duodecim_scriptorum\" title=\"Ludus duodecim scriptorum\">ludus duodecim scriptorum</a></i>, or a game played with <a href=\"/wiki/Knucklebones\" title=\"Knucklebones\">knucklebones</a> (<i>astragali</i>).\n</p><p>Latin poetry often explores the concept of <i>ludus</i> as playfulness, both in the writing of poetry as a kind of play and as a field for erotic role-playing.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \"Poetic play (<i>ludus</i>, <i>ludere</i>, <i>iocum</i>, etc.),\" Mich\u00e8le Lowrie observes, \"denotes two related things: stylistic elegance of the <a href=\"/wiki/Alexandrian_school\" title=\"Alexandrian school\">Alexandrian variety</a> and erotic poetry.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><i><a href=\"/wiki/Ludi\" title=\"Ludi\">Ludi</a></i>, always plural, were the games held in conjunction with <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_festivals\" title=\"Roman festivals\">Roman religious festivals</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ludus_(ancient_Rome)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Lusus_Troiae\" title=\"Lusus Troiae\">Lusus Troiae</a>, the Troy Game</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ludus_(ancient_Rome)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Oxford Latin Dictionary</i> (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1982, 1985 reprint), pp. 1048\u20131049.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Thomas N. Habinek, <i>The World of Roman Song: From Ritualized Speech to Social Order</i> (Johns Hopkins University Press, 2005), pp. 5, 143, <i>et passim</i>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Mich\u00e8le Lowrie, <i>Horace's Narrative Odes</i> (Oxford University Press, 1997), p. 41.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:She-wolf_suckles_Romulus_and_Remus.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/She-wolf_suckles_Romulus_and_Remus.jpg/40px-She-wolf_suckles_Romulus_and_Remus.jpg\" width=\"40\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/She-wolf_suckles_Romulus_and_Remus.jpg/60px-She-wolf_suckles_Romulus_and_Remus.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/She-wolf_suckles_Romulus_and_Remus.jpg/80px-She-wolf_suckles_Romulus_and_Remus.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"640\" data-file-height=\"480\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Rome\" title=\"Ancient Rome\">Ancient Rome</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ludus_(ancient_Rome)&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=